6th August 2015 | MH370
PRIME MINISTER NAJIB RAZAK STATEMENT ON MH370 
On 8 March 2014, flight MH370 from Kuala Lumpur to Beijing disappeared. The days, weeks and months that followed have been a period of torment for the families of those on board. 
The plane’s disappearance was without precedent. At every stage, we followed the tiny amount of evidence that existed. But, despite the efforts of 26 nations and the largest search in aviation history, from the South China Sea to the Indian Ocean, the plane could not be located. 
Neither could investigations by the world’s leading aviation experts answer why MH370 veered off course and went dark. While the plane’s disappearance remained a mystery, we have shared the anguish of those who could find no comfort. 
Last week, on 29th July, we were informed by the French authorities that part of an aircraft wing had been found on Reunion, the French island in the Indian Ocean. 
Today, 515 days since the plane disappeared, it is with a heavy heart that I must tell you that an international team of experts have conclusively confirmed that the aircraft debris found on Reunion Island is indeed from MH370. 
We now have physical evidence that, as I announced on 24th March last year, flight MH370 tragically ended in the southern Indian Ocean. 
This is a remote, inhospitable and dangerous area, and on behalf of Malaysia I would like to thank the many nations, organisations and individuals who have participated in the search. 
The burden and uncertainty faced by the families during this time has been unspeakable. It is my hope that this confirmation, however tragic and painful, will at least bring certainty to the families and loved ones of the 239 people onboard MH370. They have our deepest sympathy and prayers. 
I would like to assure all those affected by this tragedy that the government of Malaysia is committed to do everything within our means to find out the truth of what happened. MH370’s disappearance marked us as a nation. We mourn with you, as a nation. 
And I promise you this: Malaysia will always remember and honour those who were lost onboard MH370. 
ENDS

caption.text:
On 8 March 2014, flight #MH370 from Kuala Lumpur to Beijing disappeared. 
Last week, on 29th July, we were informed by the French authorities that part of an aircraft wing had been found on Reunion, the French island in the Indian Ocean.

Today, 515 days since the plane disappeared, it is with a heavy heart that I must tell you that an international team of experts have conclusively confirmed that the aircraft debris found on Reunion Island is indeed from MH370.
- Prime Minister of Malaysia

Thursday | 06082015 
I searched in my phone. Did I take any picture on 8th March 2014?

Then I found this.

On the date I was drinking coffee with girlfriends, MH370 went missing. I was looking at this display; dreaming about bookshelves, enjoying my coffee moments after work several hours before the news.

I had faith that someday the plane would be discovered. Little did I know that I would be discovering something else too.

On the 6th August 2014, exactly a year from this date, I was hospitalised after an appendicitis surgery. 7 days after the doctor was telling me that I was diagnosed with cancer.

Nothing was certain, don't you think?

When the plane was declared missing, I was one healthy woman who walked everywhere she wished.

When they are declaring the discovery of part of the plane, I am acknowledging an anniversary of my own cancer journey.

In 515 days, everything can happen.

My condolence goes to the families of MH370 passengers and crew. This might be a closure and a new opening. Your story won't be forgotten. Our thoughts and prayers will always be with you.

At the end of the day, nobody knows their ultimate closure. And that nobody includes us too.

Al-Fatihah.

#AlFatihah #GrandMother #MH370 #MalaysiaAirlines #SinChewDaily #Pray4MH370

I remember when I was in secondary school. My late grandmother would come to me with a newspaper and asked me to read certain articles that might interest her. She had probably been waiting since morning for someone to read her the articles.

I totally forgot about it until now. When I look at Sin Chew Daily but couldn't read it. I remember vividly how she would sit and look at the newspaper while I was reading. I found that very sweet.

I swear she's the most patient, elegant and sweetest grandmother I have ever known.

Let us take some time to recite al Fatihah to those who had left us and to the victims onboard MH370.

May Allah grant them and us all forgiveness.

Ameen.

caption.text:
Alphaviation Exclusive Photo
-
French officials are investigating whether plane wreckage that washed up on an Indian Ocean island is from missing flight MH370.
The debris, apparently a wing flap, was found on French-owned Reunion.
An aviation security expert said it had "incredible similarities" to a flap from a Boeing 777, the type of plane that vanished in March 2014.
But the island is a huge distance from the plane's search area and there have been other crashes much closer.
No part of the Malaysian Airlines flight has ever been found. It disappeared en route from Kuala Lumpur to Beijing with 239 people on board.
Aviation expert Xavier Tytelman said a code on the plane would be examined, promising a "definitive answer" on whether there was a link in a few days.

When Izzie (Katherine Heigl) of Grey's Anatomy was diagnosed with cancer, there was a scene when she nearly died (I thought she was dead) and this song was the soundtrack of the episode.

I love the song.
It reminded me of so many things in life even before I was diagnosed with cancer.

I posted this song on my IG on the night they have confirmed that #MH370 was lost in the Indian Ocean. That night, I shared the grief; knowing that nothing was certain in this world.

Last year, I was sick in the month of Ramadan. 
But I'm going to meet Ramadan again this year. I am still sick. Today I'm not getting up from bed because Miss Chemo wants to be the queen. I have vomitted quite a lot. Diarrhea and pain everywhere. My skin was breaking too.

I took a nap (though I resorted to reading first). When I woke up, I felt a bit better.

Looking back, I thought I would not going to last for a year. I was not going to celebrate my brother's birthday, Mother's Day, Father's Day. Or even this year's Ramadan.

But I did, right?
And I hope I can survive until Eid.

Anyway, this is not the time be down. Ramadan is a celebration. Most good memories are coming from here.

Therefore, let's keep our prayers and sense of humour, shall we?

With luck, there will be more cakes in the future.
